03855nam a22005055i 9780774817912DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112010xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748179127 a10.59962/97807748179122doi  a(DE-B1597)661875  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a342.71/0708721 aWalls, Martha Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo need of a chief for this band :bThe Maritime Mi'kmaq and Federal Electoral Legislation, 1899-1951 /cMartha Elizabeth Walls. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b9 b&w photos, 16 tables, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps, Tables, and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Mi’kmaw World in 1900 -- tContinuity and Change in Mi’kmaw Politics to 1899 -- tThe Origins of the Triennial Band Council System -- tFederal Interference and Political Persistence in Mi’kmaw Communities -- tThe Limits of Triennial Elections -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1899 the Canadian government passed legislation to replace the appointment of Mi'kmaw leaders and Mi'kmaw political practices with the triennial system, a Euro-Canadian system of democratic band council elections. Officials in Ottawa assumed the federally mandated and supervised system would redefine Mi'kmaw politics. They were wrong. Drawing on reports and correspondence of the Department of Indian Affairs, Martha Walls details the rich life of Mi'kmaw politics between 1899 and 1951. She shows that many Mi'kmaw communities rejected, ignored, or amended federal electoral legislation, while others accepted it only sporadically, not in acquiescence to Ottawa's assimilative project but to meet specific community needs and goals. Compelling and timely, this book supports Aboriginal claims to self-governance and complicates understandings of state power by showing that the Mi'kmaw, rather than succumbing to imposed political models, retained political practices that distinguished them from their Euro-Canadian neighbours.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481791240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774817912423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774817912/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles